(1, 'Agastya', 'agastya', '<h1>Agastya - The Revered Sage</h1>', '<p>Agastya is a revered sage in Hinduism, known for his extraordinary wisdom, spiritual powers, and contributions to ancient Indian culture. Here\\\'s some key information about Agastya:</p><h2>Life and Legends</h2><p>Agastya was born to the divine sage <strong>Mitra-Varuna</strong> and the <strong>Apsara</strong> (celestial nymph) Urvashi. He is often depicted as a short, stout man with a prominent belly.</p><h2>Contributions</h2><ul><li><strong>Vedic Wisdom:</strong> Agastya is credited with composing several hymns in the <em>Rigveda</em>, one of Hinduism\\\'s most sacred texts.</li><li><strong>Tamil Language:</strong> He is said to have created the Tamil language and written the first Tamil grammar book, <em>Agattiyam</em>.</li><li><strong>Ayurveda:</strong> Agastya is associated with the development of Ayurveda, the traditional Indian system of medicine.</li></ul><h2>Spiritual Significance</h2><ul><li><strong>Saptarishis:</strong> Agastya is considered one of the seven sages (<em>Saptarishis</em>) who have guided humanity throughout history.</li><li><strong>Guru:</strong> He is revered as a spiritual guru, offering guidance on the path to enlightenment.</li><li><strong>Cosmic Balance:</strong> Agastya is believed to have maintained cosmic balance by consuming the demon <em>Vatapi</em>, who threatened the gods.</li></ul><h2>Worship and Legacy</h2><ul><li><strong>Temples:</strong> Agastya is worshipped in several temples across India, particularly in the southern states of Tamil Nadu and Kerala.</li><li><strong>Festivals:</strong> His birthday, <em>Agastya Jayanti</em>, is celebrated with great fervor in some parts of India,</li><li><strong>Influence on Culture:</strong> Agastya\\\'s contributions to Tamil language, literature, and culture have had a lasting impact on Indian heritage.</li></ul><p>Agastya\\\'s life and legacy continue to inspire and guide people on their spiritual journeys.</p>', '17